    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-11-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-11-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="91"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                <head>91. National Security Decision Memorandum 92<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d91fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 1248, <persName corresp="#p_SHHH1"
                            >Saunders</persName> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss>
                            66—<gloss target="#t_NSDM1">NSDM</gloss> 92—Persian Gulf. Secret. Copies
                        were sent to <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Moorer</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MRP1">Mayo</persName>. In an attached undated memorandum,
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> authorized <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>, as head of the Interdepartmental
                        Group, to take appropriate steps to implement <gloss target="#t_NSDM1"
                            >NSDM</gloss> 92. In particular <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1"
                            >Sisco</persName> was to plan for a continuation of <gloss
                            target="#t_MIDEASTFOR1">MIDEASTFOR</gloss>; to prepare for future <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> membership of the <gloss target="#t_FAA1"
                            >FAA</gloss>, Bahrain, and Qatar; to place Kuwait on the list of
                        countries eligible to purchase U.S. arms; and to proceed with planning for
                        required diplomatic posts.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-11-07">November 7, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Administrator, Agency for International Development</item>
                    <item>The Director, U.S. Information Agency</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="0319" n="286" xml:id="pg_286"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>U.S. Policy Toward the Persian Gulf</item>
                </list>
                <p>In response to the memorandum of July 30, 1970, “Future U.S. Policy in the
                    Persian Gulf,”<note n="2" xml:id="d91fn2">See <ref target="#d83fn4">footnote 4,
                            Document 83</ref>.</note> submitted by the Chairman of the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for the Near East and
                    South Asia, the President has: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Approved a general strategy for the near term of promoting cooperation
                            between Iran and Saudi Arabia as the desirable basis for maintaining
                            stability in the Persian Gulf while recognizing the preponderance of
                            Iranian power and developing a direct U.S. relationship with the
                            separate political entities of the area.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Made a decision in principle not to reduce the U.S. naval presence in
                            the Persian Gulf at this time unless further exploration should prove it
                            politically unacceptable to friends of the U.S. in the area, in which
                            case a special report should be submitted to the President.<note n="3"
                                xml:id="d91fn3">
                                <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName> informed <persName
                                    corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> on November 4 that the
                                Departments of State and Defense were taking steps to implement
                                    <gloss target="#t_NSDM1">NSDM</gloss> 92 by maintaining <gloss
                                    target="#t_MIDEASTFOR1">MIDEASTFOR</gloss> in the Indian Ocean
                                and Persian Gulf area, homeported in Bahrain. (National Archives,
                                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential
                                Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 1276,
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SHHH1">Saunders</persName> Files, Persian
                                Gulf) <persName corresp="#p_FAAAS1">Faisal</persName> was informed
                                December 22. (Telegram 4519 from Jidda, December 23; ibid., <gloss
                                    target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                                    target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 33 PERSIAN GULF)</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Approved in principle expansion of U.S. diplomatic representation in
                            the lower Gulf but directed the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                            Under Secretaries Committee to assure that this representation is
                            imaginatively adapted to the requirements of this unique area and the
                            pursuit of U.S. interests there.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Directed the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Under Secretaries
                            Committee to review plans for U.S. technical and educational assistance
                            and cultural exchange in this area through private as well as public
                            programs to assure the development of imaginative programs consistent
                            with the strategy of promoting orderly development and local
                            responsibility for maintaining stability.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Directed that a special memorandum be prepared for the President’s
                            decision on all significant requests for military assistance from states
                            (excluding Iran and Saudi Arabia) in the Persian Gulf. This memorandum
                            should be prepared by the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                            Interdepartmental Group for Near East and South Asia and submitted to
                            the Senior Review Group by November 26, 1970.<note n="4" xml:id="d91fn4"
                                >Apparently the Review Group meeting scheduled for November 26 did
                                not take place.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
